About the year 830, Amalerius¹ put forth a work in four books, entitled Dc Officiis Ecclesiaeticic. It is a com· ment-ary on the liturgica] ceremoniee and the Divino Office.

Among the documenta which the writer made use of, there was an Ordo Rornacoa which he frequently cites as an

important authority. We recognise in it the text of Mobillon's Ordo J.. including the chapters on the paschal ceremonies, The latter, therefore, must be very ancient, but these ceremonies did not correspond with those in actual use at Rome, as Amalariue had occasion to experience in a journey which he made thither in 832 for the special purpose of pursuing his liturgical studies. Pope Gregory IV. put him into communication with his archdeacon, Theodore, who gave him all the information he required.
